{"schema":"https:\/\/ihsn.org\/schemas\/timeseries\/1.0.0","schema_version":"1.0.0","type":"timeseries","idno":"b76f14fd-a88f-497c-a6f1-37374c8f91cc","changed":"1757944936","changed_utc":"2025-04-17T09:59:38-04:00","created":"1756134477","created_utc":"2024-06-21T11:35:31-04:00","created_by":"4","changed_by":"31","metadata_information":{"idno":"META_WB_PIP_NPOOR","producers":[{"name":"Development Economics Data Group","abbr":"DECDG","affiliation":"World Bank"}],"prod_date":"2024-06-21","version_statement":{"version_notes":"Updated title formatting for consistency.","version_date":"2025-09-30","version":"1.1"},"title":"Metadata for Population living below the poverty line (million)"},"series_description":{"idno":"WB_PIP_NPOOR","version_statement":{"version":"1","version_date":"2025-09-23"},"name":"Population living below the poverty line (million)","authoring_entity":[{"name":"World Bank","uri":"https:\/\/pip.worldbank.org\/"}],"measurement_unit":"Persons","database_id":"WB_PIP","release_calendar":"In a typical year, there are two major updates (March\/April and September\/October), which bring in new survey data. These updates are documented in What\u2019s New documents (published in the Global Poverty Monitoring Technical Notes series)","alternate_identifiers":[{"identifier":"PIP database indicator ID","name":"WB.PIP.npoor.UMIC","database":"WB.PIP"},{"identifier":"PIP dataset variable name ","name":"pop_in_poverty"}],"definition_long":"Number of people, in millions, living on less than the selected poverty line (i.e. $3.00, $4.20, or $8.30) a day at the selected PPP (i.e. 2021 or 2017). This indicator is calculated by multiplying the poverty rate with the population. Poverty rates cannot be compared across PPP years. Rather, poverty rates can be compared across countries using the same PPP year (i.e. 2017 or 2021). \n\nPlease refer to: https:\/\/datanalytics.worldbank.org\/PIP-Methodology\/.","periodicity":"Annual","methodology":"Please refer to: https:\/\/datanalytics.worldbank.org\/PIP-Methodology\/","methodology_references":[{"source":"Poverty and Inequality Platform Methodology Handbook","uri":"https:\/\/datanalytics.worldbank.org\/PIP-Methodology\/"}],"aggregation_method_references":[{"source":"Poverty and Inequality Platform Methodology Handbook","uri":"https:\/\/datanalytics.worldbank.org\/PIP-Methodology\/non-technical-summary.html#step-2-constructing-welfare-aggregates"}],"limitation":"PIP extrapolations and interpolations require additional assumptions, namely that (a) growth in household income or consumption can be approximated by growth in national accounts and (b) all parts of the distribution grow at the same rate. Given these assumptions, users are cautioned against using reference-year estimates for comparing a country\u2019s poverty trend over time. For that purpose, users should rely on the survey-year estimates and are advised to take into account breaks in survey comparability. Because extrapolating and interpolating require full welfare distributions, for a country to feature in PIP, it is not sufficient that it has an international poverty rate at a survey year, it must have unit record data or grouped data. For more details on the methodology and types of input data accepted by PIP, please visit the PIP Methodology Handbook and the Global Poverty Monitoring Technical Notes.","quality":"In a typical year, there are two major updates (March\/April and September\/October), which bring in new survey data. These updates are documented in What\u2019s New documents (published in the Global Poverty Monitoring Technical Notes series). When necessary, intermediate updates are made to correct errors as soon as possible. Updates are documented here: https:\/\/worldbank.github.io\/PIP_data_updates\/.","time_periods":[{"start":"1963","end":"2023"}],"contacts":[{"name":"Raul Andres Castaneda Aguilar","position":"TTL","affiliation":"DECID","email":"acastanedaa@worldbank.org"},{"name":"Nishant Yonzan","position":"Colla